nodes.body: Just wondering: Why did you open a new PR rather than reusing the existing one?

> Just wondering: Why did you open a new PR rather than reusing the existing one?

I wanted to reuse the name of the branch for another project, as I realized it's more convenient for me to work on a single repository and then open a new branch every time I want to make a pull request. I'm not sure if I could have reused the old PR while doing that (I think Github closed it automatically when I renamed the branch).

Apologies for the confusion, I hope everything is ok!
Oh I see. Yeah, avoid renaming branches as a general rule of thumb.
Yeah I know, it's just that I made a poor choice the first time. Shouldn't happen again!

```suggestion
lemma ofSym_map {n : ℕ} {σ τ : Type*} [DecidableEq σ] [DecidableEq τ] (e : σ ≃ τ) (s : Sym σ n) :
    Nat.Partition.ofSym (s.map e) = Nat.Partition.ofSym s := by
  simp only [ofSym, Sym.val_eq_coe, Sym.coe_map, toFinset_val, mk.injEq]
  rw [Multiset.dedup_map_of_injective e.injective]
  simp only [map_map, Function.comp_apply]
  congr; funext i
  rw [← Multiset.count_map_eq_count' e _ e.injective]
```
It seems more readable.
Can you add a (very) short description of each declaration?
Aren't they already there?
I mean like in line 23.
Ah I see! Sorry!
`f : ℕ → MvPolynomial σ R` can be a variable (you use it several times).
Probably even `{n : \N}`.

```suggestion
  cases n <;> simp [esymmMu]
```
This can be `simp`.
Cans also be `simp`.

```suggestion
  simp [hsymm, ← Multiset.prod_hom']
```
In general there is no need to squeeze a `simp` at the end of a proof.

```suggestion
  simp only [psum, pow_zero, sum_const, nsmul_eq_mul, mul_one]
  rfl
```
But it's better to squeeze it if it's not at the end.

```suggestion
theorem psumMu_onePart {n : ℕ} (npos : n > 0) :
```
This seems to have been forgotten.
Why the swap? Also, in the presence of several goals, can you use `· ` to improve readability? Thanks!
Is it worth to define this `f` outside the proof?

```suggestion
  convert_to X i = Multiset.prod (Multiset.map X {i})
  simp only [Multiset.map_singleton, Multiset.prod_singleton]
```
The `convert_to` tactic is designed to this type of situations.
Here `show ...` also works. Is there a lemma we can rewrite instead of using `show`? It would make the proof more robust.

I tried but I can't get rid of that. Also I defined the two equivalences outside the lemmas, but I don't think it's worth it for both. There is probably a way to get rid of `ofSym_equiv_onePart`, but I can't find any elegant alternative.
I mean, stating explicitly the thing `show` is doing here (in a separate lemma, the proof will be `rfl`) and rewrite the lemma. But don't worry too much if it is complicated.
Better now?
Yes, that's good, thanks!
Same as above.

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion ((Nat.Partition.ofSym_equiv_onePart σ) i : Multiset σ) = {i} := rfl ```

```suggestion
```
Is this import needed? Everything works fine on my end without it.
Shouldn't the linter complain if it's unused?

```suggestion
      (toFinset s.1).sum fun a ↦ count a s.1 := rfl
```

Actually, why not use the notation?
```suggestion
      ∑ a ∈ toFinset s.1, count a s.1 := rfl
```
The latter doesn't work on my build. It gives `elaboration function for 'BigOperators.bigsum' has not been implemented' error.
Have you `open scoped BigOperators`?
It's not scoped, but `BigOperators' is opened on line 49.
It's because you were on an old version of master that didn't have the notation yet. I've fixed it.

```suggestion
  (μ.parts.map f).prod
```

```suggestion
      obtain ⟨a, rfl⟩ := List.length_eq_one.mp h
      exact List.eq_of_mem_singleton (perm.mem_iff.mp <| List.head_mem _)
```
Not sure why that's happening. Will try to minimise
Thanks!

I think the `_of_injective` is easily inferrable
```suggestion
theorem dedup_map [DecidableEq β] {f : α → β} (hinj : f.Injective)
```

```suggestion
    muProduct σ R f (.indiscrete 0) = 1 := by simp [muProduct]
```
and everywhere else
Fixed.
I don't quite like how you name `hsymmMu` after the free variable `μ`. Is this really standard in the literature?

I don't like it either, and it's really not standard. The standard notation would be just h_\mu. In the literature there is no distinction (in notation) between h_n and h_\mu, so I would really like to call it just hsymm, but the name is taken. I'm very much open to suggestions.
Maybe `hsymmPartition` or `hsymmPart`?
Sounds good. Do you have a similar suggestion for `muProduct`?
Honestly, I'm not sure we need `muProduct` as a def? Like, writing `(μ.parts.map f).prod` isn't so bad.
Yeah you're right. I got rid of it.

It is (usually) a bad idea to put explicit arguments in `variable` statements as you tend to forget they are there when writing lemma statements. It's better to instead only have the implicit variables declared in a `variable` statement.
On line 181, some stuff breaks if I remove the explicit declaration. Should I do that anyway and fix the rest?
Yes please :)
Done!
Of course this screwed up many things.

Should I explicitly declare these variables every time (which is a bit cumbersome) or make them implicit and change the rest of the library accordingly? I'm leaning towards the latter, as declaring explicitly `\sigma` and `R` every time is really annoying for someone who's working on symmetric functions. Is that ok?
Oh sorry, I see those are used explicitly almost everywhere. I would like to retract my first claim and declare `variable (σ R)` is fine here (but please not `(n : ℕ)`)
Uh I already changed it everywhere, should I revert?
Yes sorry 🤐
I think the misunderstanding was that I referring to `(n : ℕ)` but you took that to mean `(σ R)` as well
Well you said 'explicit variables', not `(n : \N)`. Anyway, reverting is a quick process, I did it!
True, but as a matter of fact reviewers shouldn't ask you to change an existing pattern in a PR that adds new code. That's a bad reviewing practice

It's not called `onePart`, right?
```suggestion
theorem psumMu_indiscrete {n : ℕ} (npos : n > 0) :
```
I think you should inline this definition. It's very easy to simply write `(μ.parts.map f).prod`
Done.
cc @eric-wieser
Do I have to do anything?
Merge master to get the lemma from #14282 and remove your now redundant version
I find it funny that I called the lemma `dedup_map_of_injective` and it got renamed to `dedup_map`, only for someone else to add it to the library as `dedup_map_of_injective`. 😶

Two things:
1. Never write `a > b`, but `b < a`. Similarly for `≥`/`≤`.
2. We prefer `n ≠ 0` to `0 < n` when `n : Nat`.

```suggestion
theorem muProduct_indiscrete_of_pos {n : ℕ} (npos : n ≠ 0) (f : ℕ → MvPolynomial σ R) :
```
Fixed!
You don't need to write those "equational lemmas" yourself. `rw [psumPart]` will do that for you
Yeah you're right, I just mimicked what was there already. Got rid of them.
This one is still around
Must have been in one of the reverted commits.
I don't really understand this name. What is the `onePart` referring to.
I missed it after renaming "onePart" to "indiscrete". Fixed that.
Please expand this docstring to include the informal definition of "complete homogeneous symmetric polynomial".
Idem.
